Volume 141, June 2024, 107166

Characterizing urban spatial structure through built form typologies: A new framework using clustering ensembles

Author links open overlay panel,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.landusepol.2024.107166Get rights and content
Under a Creative Commons license
Open access

Highlights

  • •
    A novel clustering analytical framework for studying urban built form is developed.
  • •
    The proposed framework utilizes clustering ensembles to yield stable results.
  • •
    The results identified eight distinct typologies of built forms of Guangzhou.
  • •
    The proposed clustering analytical framework can be applied to other urban research settings.

Abstract

Prior research on urban form typologies has largely relied on qualitative classification methods, resulting in subjective and limited analyses. Recently, the emerging data-intensive studies often use a single clustering algorithm and parameter setting, raising concerns about the reliability of the findings. This paper introduces a novel clustering analytical framework for conducting typological studies on urban form that yield stable and reliable results. We employ clustering ensembles, which can combine multiple clustering algorithms to further provide a comprehensible output that facilitates interpretation and knowledge generation. By applying the new framework using 3D building data in Guangzhou, we identify eight typologies of urban built forms and reveal a consistent polycentric pattern across different clustering algorithms and parameter settings. The findings have implications for urban land use planning and regulations by integrating 3D representations of urban form.

1. Introduction

A city is a complex entity characterized by both disorderly and inherently ordered urban forms, exhibiting a wealth of diversity and intricate complexity (Batty, 2009, Kropf, 2009, Williams, 2013). Ongoing rapid urbanization and urban renewal processes further contribute to the hybridization of our built environment with the emergence of new architectural structures. Consequently, this complexity makes it challenging to perceive and comprehend the underlying spatial structure that reflects the physical arrangement or layout of the built environment (Anderson et al., 1996, de Oliveira, 2022). In this context, typological analysis serves as a well-established research approach to unravel the complex and hybrid built environment (Moudon, 1994, Yiftachel, 1989). This method involves classifying observations into groups based on similarities while highlighting distinctions between these groups. Typological analysis aims to unify observations and generate new knowledge. Its purpose is to uncover fundamental types and elucidate the complementary relationships among these typologies (Güney, 2007). In the realm of urban form, the typological study enables researchers and planners to focus on a small number of representative cases (Li and Quan, 2020) and gain a comprehensive and concise view of the overall spatial structure by examining the spatial pattern of different typologies.
In A Theory of Good City Form, Lynch (1984) argued that the quality of a place results from the collective influence of both the urban form and the society that occupies it. Urban form plays a pivotal role in shaping resident behavior and exhibits correlations with environmental performance (Wheeler, 2015). Specifically, the impact of urban form extends to influencing residents' choices in transportation, shaping their daily experiences, impacting racial concentration, and influencing public health outcomes (Frank and Engelke, 2001, Mouratidis et al., 2019, Soga et al., 2015, Talen et al., 2018). Different urban forms manifest varied effects in terms of heat islands, energy consumption, greenhouse gas emissions, and air quality (Chen et al., 2019, Liu et al., 2021, Quan and Li, 2021, Zhang et al., 2022). The systematic study of urban form typologies represents a higher echelon of information extraction and synergy, which is a stratified sampling process of the built environment. Rather than scrutinizing the relationship between outcome variables and multiple built environment indicators (e.g., building volume, building height), researchers can explore the association between outcome variables and urban form typologies. This stratification approach cannot only identify the subgroup effect but also yield more direct and lucid implications, as typologies are more comprehensible to human understanding and align with cognitive processes.
There is a large volume of existing studies that explored urban spatial structure, however, they mainly focused on economic indicators such as land rent (Alonso, 1964), population density (Clark, 1951), employment density (Giuliano and Small, 1991, McDonald, 1987), land use (Keys et al., 2007, Pan et al., 2021, Wu and Yeh, 1999), location big data (Hui et al., 2020, Yang et al., 2019) and georeferenced social media data (Chen et al., 2019, Deng et al., 2019). Conventional research on the urban physical structure and urban form typologies relied on knowledge-based and qualitative classification (Conzen, 2004, Conzen, 1960, Wheeler, 2015, Whitehand et al., 2011). Among these approaches, the historico-geographical method pioneered by the geographer M. R. G. Conzen stands out as highly influential. This approach seeks to elucidate the physical urban structure of a town by scrutinizing architectural elements and their evolution over time. It is widely adopted in European and East Asian urban contexts, including China and Japan (Satoh, 2008, Whitehand et al., 2011). On the other hand, Wheeler (2015) conducted a global examination encompassing 24 metropolitan regions, identifying 27 fundamental urban form typologies. This research primarily relies on expert knowledge of physical urban form and use. However, it is noteworthy that these studies are characterized by their time-consuming nature, constrained to a small area, and relative subjectivity, as they heavily depend on human judgment.
The availability of extensive spatial data allows urban form studies to use data-driven classification on a large scale. This clustering process can effectively identify urban form typologies and is expected to generate knowledge. Several studies have utilized clustering algorithms to identify urban form typologies (Berghauser Pont et al., 2019, Gil et al., 2012, Li and Quan, 2020, Schirmer and Axhausen, 2019, Song and Knaap, 2007). The characteristics of the clusters obtained from the clustering algorithms can serve as representations of various urban form typologies. For example, Song and Knaap (2007) applied clustering analysis utilizing diverse urban form indicators within Portland's neighborhoods. Subsequently, they performed a cross-tabulation of the discerned typologies, linking them to their respective age categories. The primary objective of their research was to comprehend emerging urban form characteristics and their spatial distribution. Berghauser Pont et al. (2019) employed statistical clustering methods across five European cities to delineate contemporary urban forms and facilitate quantitative inter-city comparisons. Their study identified typologies of streets, plots, and buildings independently. Through comparative analyses, distinctive typologies emerged at each level, offering insights into city-specific urban configurations. Li and Quan (2020) identified nine urban form typologies based on building, street, and plot attributes within Seoul. Although these investigations predominantly focused on typological outcomes, there was a tendency to overlook the comprehensive structure and interconnections of these typologies across the entire urban fabric of a city.
Notably, the reliability of data-driven studies on urban form is a matter of concern, primarily due to the reliance on a single clustering algorithm and parameter setting in most previous studies. For example, Gil et al. (2012), Song and Knaap (2007), and Yu et al. (2022) utilized the widely used cluster analysis K-means, whereas Li and Quan (2020) and Berghauser Pont et al. (2019) applied the Gaussian mixture model (GMM) method and principal component analysis (PCA), respectively. These studies solely depended on the results obtained from a single-parameter setting of the respective algorithms, such as the cluster number for K-means and GMM, and the component number for PCA. Boongoen and Iam-On (2018) identified two major challenges in applying clustering algorithms. First, the difficulty lies in selecting the appropriate technique, as different algorithms may uncover various structures. Second, specifying the algorithm’s settings becomes a challenge, as a single algorithm with different parameters can reveal various structures in the same dataset. Consequently, the reliability of these studies remains subject to question.
To fill the gaps and improve the data-driven urban form studies, we introduce a novel clustering analytical framework using clustering ensembles. Compared with using a single clustering method, clustering ensembles can yield more stable solutions and improve the quality of clustering results (Boongoen and Iam-On, 2018, Ghosh and Acharya, 2011). This approach can utilize diverse clustering algorithms to capture different aspects of the underlying structure of the data (Alqurashi & Wang, 2019). Furthermore, the combined results obtained through clustering ensembles provide a comprehensible output that facilitates interpretation and knowledge generation. Clustering ensembles enable the integration of clustering results obtained from diverse algorithms with varying parameters into a unified outcome. In our study, we employed this framework to explore urban built forms generated by the 3D building data, focusing not only on the final integrated typologies but also on the overall spatial structure by further interpreting the typologies. Consequently, our framework presented and examined both the clustering ensemble results and individual clustering results, enabling us to investigate the presence of a consistent spatial structure across different clustering algorithms and parameter settings. Besides the studies on built environment, our analytical framework can also be used in other types of urban analytics that require spatial and clustering analysis, such as urban mobility pattern analysis and urban land use pattern analysis.
The paper is organized as follows: Section 2 introduces the site and data and provides a detailed overview of the analytical framework employed in the study. In Section 3, we present the results of our analysis focusing on Guangzhou, highlighting the identified built-form typologies and the overall spatial structure of the area. Section 4 explores the implications of urban governance and planning practices within the scope of our study. Finally, Section 5 includes concluding remarks, potential limitations, and future directions for research.

2. Data and methodology

2.1. Study area and data

We chose Guangzhou, one of the four largest megacities of China, as our studied site because of its complex built environment. Guangzhou has experienced a diverse urban development process including urban expansion, city merger, urban center renewal (Li et al., 2019), and informal settlement densification (van Oostrum, 2021), creating a hybrid built environment. The spatial structure can be predefined as a polycentric model with a large core urban center and several subcenters that were previous county-level cities but merged into Guangzhou as districts in recent years. Besides modern buildings, historical buildings, industrial buildings, and informal settlements (urban villages) exist and cover a considerable area of Guangzhou, resulting in diverse urban built-form typologies. In this regard, we employed the 3D building data, which contains 473,727 buildings1 with elevation information covering most of the urban area.

2.2. Clustering analytical framework

Our analytical framework can be divided into the following several steps and corresponds to various subsequent sections in this study. Initially, we extracted urban built-form indicators from the 3D building data of Guangzhou for all units of analysis (Section 2.2.1). Subsequently, we employed diverse clustering algorithms to analyze the grid data. For each clustering algorithm, we selected multiple optimal values for the cluster number (referred to as k) from two predefined ranges, primarily guided by domain knowledge. After obtaining results from different algorithms with distinct optimal k values, we employed clustering ensembles to consolidate all the outcomes. Once again, we determined the optimal k values for the clustering ensembles using internal measures (Section 2.2.2). To facilitate result comparison, we reindexed all the outcomes based on Jaccard similarity (Section 2.2.3). Following the acquisition of the reindexed results, we initially focused on the clustering ensembles that demonstrate the best performance (3.1 Typologies of clustering ensembles, 3.2 Spatial structure of clustering ensemble) and explored the consistent spatial structure across all clustering results (Section 3.3).

2.2.1. Units of analysis

In this study, we systematically considered the potential issues of the modifiable areal unit problem (MAUP). Although various strategies have been suggested to address the Modifiable Areal Unit Problem, none provides a one-size-fits-all solution (Dark and Bram, 2007). In our study, we primarily adopted the solutions proposed by Openshaw (1984) and Jelinski and Wu (1996).
We firstly followed Openshaw’s approach that acknowledges and mitigates MAUP by aligning with the “objects of geographical inquiry.” This approach suggests that researchers should carefully select an appropriate areal unit and explicitly recognize the scale (areal unit) at which their conclusions are drawn. For our analysis, we selected a grid size of 500 m x 500 m, reflecting the general size of local blocks in Guangzhou. Regarding the areal unit, this grid also offers a more accurate representation of the city's block structure than alternative shapes, such as hexagons, particularly in the context of Guangzhou. We also opted not to use administrative boundaries for defining area units due to their inconsistent sizes throughout the city. Further, selecting the appropriate size for the areal unit is crucial, as choosing units that are either too large or too small can complicate the accurate representation of built forms. The 500 m grid unit, which has been employed in numerous studies within China (Fan et al., 2018, Li et al., 2020, Luo et al., 2021, Sun et al., 2022, Wu et al., 2020, Wu et al., 2023), Japan (Lwin et al., 2016), as well as Korea (Li and Quan, 2020), which proves to be an effective unit to capture the variance in built forms while maintaining sensitivity to variations among different neighborhoods.
In addition, Jelinski and Wu (1996) recommended the concept of the “sensitivity analysis approach”, which assesses the sensitivity of the results when the areal unit varies. In our study, we also applied the same clustering framework to adjacent units of both larger and smaller scales, specifically 250 m and 750 m. Within each unit of analysis, we assessed indicators derived from the 3D building data encompassed by the grid.

2.2.2. 3D urban built form indicators

Existing literature on urban form indicators concluded that indicators derived from contemporary quantitative investigations can be systematically classified into six categories: dimension, shape, spatial distribution, intensity, connectivity, and diversity (Fleischmann et al., 2021). These classifications are based on three conceptual scales, namely small, medium, and large. Among these, dimension, shape, and intensity are capable of direct measurement at the level of individual buildings, while the remaining categories entail quantification from larger-scale elements, such as streets, blocks, or entire built-up areas. Given our specific emphasis on the examination of built forms at a small scale, we have selectively chosen metrics from the categories of dimension, shape, and intensity to effectively capture the distinctive characteristics of the built environment in our study (see Table 1).

Table 1. Urban built form indices.

TypeAttributeCodeDescriptionReference

The intensity indicators, pivotal in shaping the built environment, are particularly influential in China, where development control is predominantly regulated through FAR. In addition to FAR, our analysis incorporates BCOVR and BCONR to complement FAR. These intensity indicators have found application in urban form-related studies, encompassing areas such as energy consumption (Li et al., 2018, Li et al., 2023) and urban morphological regionalization (Yang et al., 2022). In terms of the dimension category, it primarily focuses on a singular yet crucial dimension of built elements. In our study, the dimension category centers on height indicators, a key and highly scrutinized aspect of buildings. AH and HV serve as direct measures of building height characteristics, while TOWERP elucidates distinctive ground-level structures. These indicators are often outcomes influenced by both land value and fire protection codes. Notably, recent studies incorporating 3D building data commonly include at least AH in their indicator system (Cao et al., 2021, Huang and Wang, 2019, Li et al., 2021, Wu et al., 2022, Xi et al., 2023, Xia et al., 2022, Yan et al., 2021, Yin, 2017, Zhang et al., 2022). In studies focusing on air quality (Zhang et al., 2022) and urban vibrancy (Xia et al., 2022), HV and TOWERP are also included. The final category pertains to shape, where indicators are intricately linked to building functions. To capture these characteristics, our analysis includes ABA, BAV, and ASCR, which have also been used in recent research (Xia et al., 2022, Zhang et al., 2022).
Within each category, three specific indicators were selected to ensure equal weighting in the subsequent clustering analysis. After extracting the indicators, we standardized the attributes of the grid data to ensure that the clustering algorithms were not influenced by varying input feature scales. We applied min-max scaling and normalized all the features to the range of 0–1 in the standardization.

2.2.3. Clustering algorithms and cluster number determination

Appendix Table 1 is a brief description of these six algorithms. We applied five commonly used clustering algorithms, namely, K-Means, GMM, hierarchy clustering (HC), Fuzzy C-Means (FCM), and spectral clustering (SC).2 Subsequently, we adopted the meta-clustering algorithm (MCLA) from the study of Strehl and Ghosh (2002) to ensemble the results. The clustering ensembles can integrate different clustering results even if they have different k values and customize k when outputting the final meta result. MCLA is a method introduced to address the cluster ensemble problem. It operates by clustering clusters and provides confidence estimates of cluster membership at the object level. In MCLA, each cluster is represented by a hyperedge. The algorithm aims to group and collapse related hyperedges, assigning each object to the most strongly participating collapsed hyperedge. The similarity measure in this algorithm is based on the binary Jaccard measure. Compared with other clustering ensemble algorithms, such as the cluster-based similarity partitioning algorithm, which is simple but time-consuming, MCLA is nearly linear in the sample number (Strehl and Ghosh, 2002). In our research, we first conduct individual clustering analyses with the Scikit-learn library and Fuzzy-c-means library in Python. We then employed the ClusterEnsembles library (available at
https://github.com/827916600/ClusterEnsembles) in Python to conduct the MCLA.
We determined the optimal value of k by considering domain knowledge and internal measures. The purpose of our study is to extract urban-built typologies and identify their spatial patterns. Therefore, the number of clusters should be large enough to represent the diverse existing buildings but small enough for easy comprehension. Prior data-driven urban form studies conducted at a city level have suggested that k typically ranges from 5 to 10 (Berghauser Pont et al., 2019, Gil et al., 2012, Li and Quan, 2020, Song and Knaap, 2007, Yu et al., 2022). To enhance stability, we defined two ranges for k: 5–10 (Range 1) and 10–15 (Range 2). For each individual algorithm, we selected two optimal k values within the aforementioned ranges (5–10 and 10–15) based on the internal measure, the silhouette coefficient (SHC) (Xu et al., 2016). Fig. 1 presents the SHC scores of algorithms with different k and the selected k for different algorithms. These ten selected clustering results with optimal k values were for further clustering ensembles.
Next, we ensembled all the previously selected clustering results using MCLA. The result of a specified k value in MCLA may be slightly different based on various random seeds, which can also slightly affect the performance in SHC for each k value. To improve the robustness, for each k in the range of 5–15, we calculated the results with 50 random seeds and selected the result of the best performance in SHC scores. Fig. 1 also displays the final SHC score with different k of cluster ensembles through MCLA.3 To gain an improved understanding of the ensemble results, we explored the ensemble results with k of 8, and 13 in the later section also because the SHC scores of clustering ensembles at k of 8 and 13 perform the best in their corresponding range.

2.2.4. Reindexing the clustering results

The clustering algorithms exhibited variations in the assignment of indices to clusters, where the assigned indices merely represent categorical rather than graduated values. Consequently, similar clusters obtained from different clustering algorithms may be assigned various indices, posing a challenge for identifying spatial patterns. To enhance the interpretation of clustering results across various algorithms, we proposed a reindexing approach based on Jaccard similarity. The Jaccard similarity is defined as the size of the intersection of the sets divided by the size of their union (Pandit and Gupta, 2011). This approach aims to reassign clusters into consistent indices, particularly grouping clusters with similar compositions under the same index so that similar clusters can be visualized in the same color on the map. However, different colors do not necessarily mean the clusters are quite different in urban built-form indices.
We selected the clustering ensemble result (k=13) as the reference cluster because it has the largest number of clusters, whereas the results obtained from other algorithms require reindexing. For each set of clusters that require reindexing, we calculated the pairwise Jaccard index between the clusters and the reference clusters. Subsequently, for each cluster that requires reindexing, we assigned it the index of the reference cluster with the highest corresponding Jaccard index. To prevent multiple clusters from being assigned to the same index, we performed the reindexing process sequentially based on cluster size, prioritizing large clusters. Furthermore, once an index has been assigned, the corresponding reference cluster was excluded from the search for the highest Jaccard index in subsequent cluster reindexing iterations. This method ensures that similar clusters of sufficient size are prioritized for reassignment to the same index.

3. Results and discussions

Fig. 2 depicts the spatial distribution of clustering ensembles at resolutions of 250 m, 500 m, and 750 m (additional detailed results for 250 m and 750 m are provided in Appendix figures 28–51). The results exhibit a consistent polycentric pattern, with the 250 m and 500 m resolutions revealing more detailed aspects of the overall spatial structure. Given that 500 m represents a community scale in China, this section focuses on the results obtained at this resolution for the sake of brevity and clarity.
In our analysis of the 500 m unit, we first examined the result from clustering ensembles of the best performance and then explored the consistent spatial structure across all clustering results. Fig. 3 shows the results of the clustering ensembles, wherein both outcomes have been reindexed using the clustering ensemble result (k=13) as the reference. Additionally, Fig. 4 depicts the difference between the two clustering results.
Based on Fig. 4, we observed a significant similarity between the major clusters (Cluster 7, 10, and 9) in both results, while differences mainly occur in the minor clusters. This is also evident in the spatial distribution of the clusters displayed in Fig. 3, where the primary spatial structures align closely, but minor variations are noticeable in local places. In Section 2.2.3, we have discussed the approach and criteria to determine the optimized value of k in each step. Considering that the clustering ensemble with k=8 offers a more concise representation of the physical structure and performs the best in SHC among all clustering ensemble results, we narrowed our focus to this particular outcome in the subsequent sections.

3.1. Typologies of clustering ensembles

We then conducted an in-depth analysis of the identified typologies (clusters) within the clustering ensembles with k=8. Our focus is to examine the characteristics of these clusters, which serve as representations of various urban built-form typologies. To comprehend these typologies, we presented the kernel density estimation (KDE) curve in Fig. 5, showcasing various standardized indicators of the clusters. Fig. 6 highlights eight representative built-form typologies based on the clustering results.4
Cluster 3 can be characterized as a high-density skyscraper typology, exhibiting the highest means of FAR and second-highest means of AH and TOWERP. Similarly, cluster 4 shares similar distributions of AH and TOWERP with cluster 3 but with lower means of FAR, and BCOVR. We define cluster 4 as a sparse high-rise typology. This typology represents that the high-rise buildings are concentrated in some places, creating a contrast between the tall structures and the surrounding low-rise or open spaces. Additionally, cluster 2 can be described as a sparse moderate-density typology, displaying intermediate means of FAR, BCOVR, and AH.
Cluster 0 stands out with the highest means of FAR and BCONR. This cluster can be classified as a vernacular high-density typology due to its alignment with the characteristics of vernacular built form. Furthermore, it predominantly occupies locations within the historical districts of Guangzhou. Similarly, cluster 9 shares similar distributions of BCONR, BCOVR, and FAR with cluster 0 but with lower means of TOWERP and AH. Cluster 8 represents a mixed urban village and industrial typology. It captures a mixed-built environment comprising urban villages, small-scale industrial buildings, and multi-story residential structures. Conversely, cluster 7 exhibits the lowest means of BCONR, BCOVR, and FAR. Therefore, cluster 7 can be defined as a sparsely built typology, such as small villages, or undeveloped land.
In addition, cluster 11 displays the remarkably highest means of ABA and ASCR but relatively small means of BCONR. This typology typically represents mega plants or warehouses. Finally, we define cluster 10 as a compact industrial typology.
We conducted a comparative analysis of our eight typologies with the basic types of the built landscape as delineated in the study of Wheeler (2015). Wheeler identified 27 basic typologies in his research, and our investigation revealed a noteworthy correspondence. Specifically, clusters 0 and 2 exhibit similarities with the Quasi-grid, while clusters 3 and 4 align with the Super-block typology. Moreover, clusters 10 and 11 fall within the category of Workplace boxes, and cluster 7 bears a resemblance to Incremental/mixed. Nevertheless, the typology of cluster 9, characterized by a blend of urban village and industrial elements, poses a challenge for direct comparison. This particular cluster also shares attributes with informal settlements, displaying significantly higher density than the Organic typology in the study of Wheeler (2015). In summary, our identified typologies generally converge with the findings of Wheeler (2015), albeit with a finer and more localized perspective on urban form.

3.2. Spatial structure of clustering ensemble

In this section, we aim to characterize the physical spatial structure based on the eight identified typologies, with a specific focus on the results obtained from the clustering ensemble with k=8 (Fig. 7). The presence of a polycentric pattern in Guangzhou is notable, characterized by a significant main urban area along with multiple small urban areas. The large urban area exhibits a structured composition consisting of a prominent central core and three corridors, namely, the north, south, and east corridors.
The central core demonstrates a concentric arrangement, comprising five layers represented by clusters 7, 10, 9, 0, and 3. The innermost of the core is cluster 3, representing the high-density skyscraper typology. This specific location corresponds to the Tianhe central business district. Adjacent to cluster 3 is cluster 0, the vernacular high-density typology, which is mainly located in the historical areas. Following Cluster 0, we find the mixed urban village and industrial typology (cluster 9), the compact industrial typology (cluster 10), and the sparsely built typology. Notably, the AH and TOWERP values gradually decrease as we move from cluster 3 to cluster 7 (Fig. 5). Similarly, a distinctive gradient pattern is observed in the three corridors, extending from the inner sections toward the outer areas. These corridors are formed by clusters 7, 10, 9, and 0, with particular emphasis on the north and east corridors.
When examining the three small urban areas in Conghua, Huadu, and Zengchen, we observed a concentric circle pattern consisting of clusters 7,10, 4, and 3. Similar to the main urban area, the high-density skyscraper typology (cluster 3) composites the cores of these small urban areas. In the middle layer is cluster 4, which represents the sparse high-rise typology. This typology is predominantly found in suburban areas, where high-rise buildings are intentionally concentrated in a suburban setting. In terms of the industrial sectors, the industrial typologies represented by clusters 10 and 11 are mainly situated in the northern region of the east corridor, whereas some can be found on the outskirts of the urban areas.

3.3. Spatial structure across different algorithms and parameter settings

We presented the spatial distribution of clustering results obtained from various algorithms with different respective optimal values of k in two ranges, as shown in Fig. 8 and Fig. 9 (Detailed results for each algorithm and parameter setting can be seen in Appendix Fig. 3-27). All the results have been reindexed using the result of clustering ensembles with k=13 as a reference. A consistent pattern of polycentricity can be observed in other algorithm results for Guangzhou, as illustrated in Fig. 3, Fig. 8, and Fig. 9. This pattern is characterized by the presence of a large continuous urban area along with multiple small urban areas. Similarly, the large urban area in all the results demonstrates a structured composition, consisting of a significant central core and three corridors that extend toward the north, south, and east. The concentric circle pattern observed in the small urban areas is also evident across all the results, displaying either a two-layer or three-layer concentricity. Notably, results with a small number of k provide a clear depiction of the urban structure, given the relatively small number of typologies. By contrast, results with a large number of k offer a detailed representation of the urban form and its intricate characteristics.
We further compared the results among different algorithms in Fig. 10 and Fig. 11. The comparisons between different parameters within the same algorithms are shown in Appendix Fig. 7, 12, 17, 22, and 27. It is noteworthy that while some similarities exist in the classification of Clusters 7 and 9 within Range 1 (5−10), and Clusters 7 and 10 within Range 2 (10−15), there are significant variations in the results concerning other clusters. This observation suggests that different algorithms can capture diverse underlying structures within the data. Solely relying on a single algorithm may raise concerns about the reliability of the findings. Consequently, employing clustering ensemble techniques can offer a more stable clustering solution.
We have conducted a comparative analysis between the identified spatial structure and previous official planning documents. Our findings corroborate the presence of a polycentric structure and development corridors, as outlined in the Conceptual Plan of Guangzhou (2000), the Guangzhou Master Plan (2003–2020), and the Guangzhou Master Plan (2017–2035). Furthermore, we have compared our results with alternative data sources to further validate our findings. Specifically, our results align with the urban structure identified using nighttime light data, point of interest data, and WorldPop data (He et al., 2023). The urban structure identified based on the geographical location data of APP users (Wang et al., 2022) also supports our findings.
We also compared our findings with existing studies conducted in other countries. Although they usually have limited analysis of overall urban physical structure, our results can still be juxtaposed with these investigations. Based on the results of Berghauser Pont et al. (2019) particularly their clustering analysis of building types, a distinct concentric pattern is evident in the primary urban areas of London, Amsterdam, Stockholm, Gothenburg, and Eskilstuna. Similarly, Wheeler’s (2015) results of Atlanta and Beijing reveal a polycentric pattern at the overall scale and a concentric pattern within the main urban areas. The results of our study align with these international studies. However, in the research conducted by Li and Quan (2020), no discernible polycentric or concentric pattern emerges in the case of Seoul.

4. Implications of urban governance and planning practice

The implications of this study are fourfold. Firstly, it offers frameworks for revealing the physical structure of a city, enabling both the public and decision-makers to comprehend the prevailing conditions of the built environment. Grounded in the existing conditions of physical structure, decision-makers and planners can formulate more sustainable strategies for land use planning and control overall growth, thereby facilitating issues such as spatial mismatch and urban sprawl. Furthermore, in the context of China, the urbanization process is experiencing a deceleration with over-investment of physical infrastructure (Liu and Luo, 2019, Sun et al., 2023). A clearer understanding of the urban physical structure holds the potential to enhance decision-making in future infrastructure investment. This can enhance urban efficiency, sustainability, and the overall quality of life.
Second, this study has implications for form-based codes and urban design guidelines. The trajectory of urban planning systems has evolved from traditional zoning to form-based codes (Chen, 2016, Garde et al., 2015, Talen, 2009). Various countries, such as the United States and Europe with their form-based codes, and China with its urban design guidelines, have implemented the detailed control for urban form. Our research aims to identify existing form typologies within the urban landscape, serving as a foundational resource for the development of form-based codes. If further studies can evaluate the performance of identified form typologies, subsequent formulation of form-based codes can be informed by these studies, thereby fostering the incorporation of more environmentally sustainable urban forms within the cityscape. Furthermore, this study highlights the technical feasibility of integrating urban topology and form-based codes into the urban e-governance frameworks (Walters, 2011) and smart community design (e.g., Fang et al., 2022).
Additionally, typological studies occupy a central role in the field of urban design, playing a crucial part in professional practice. Urban form topologies emerge as indispensable tools directly employed by urban planners and designers. These form typologies provide essential frames of reference for the generation of urban form (Tice, 1993). The urban form typology library, in turn, becomes a valuable resource for addressing specific design challenges. When conceptualizing large-scale developments, planners and designers can readily select appropriate form typologies, treating them as integral components that integrate with existing adjacent structures. Regarding architectural education, an understanding of a limited set of typologies enables planners and designers to efficiently grasp the historical and contemporary conditions of urban artifacts (Tice, 1993). If typological studies incorporate temporal information, the evolution of form typologies and physical structures within cities can be traced. This approach could markedly enhance the dynamic e-profile of the urban built environment, benefiting smart city governance.
Finally, the depiction of a city's layout through urban form typology offers an additional governance and management perspective beyond conventional land use, administrative, and census tract maps. On a citywide scale, governance strategies, such as traffic management, urban conservation, and public safety measures, can be tailored to boundaries integrated with form typologies. At the neighborhood level, those with identical or similar built-form typologies may also mutually adopt governance strategies. This is because spatial divisions between social groups are closely tied to the urban form (Talen et al., 2018). Within a shared form typology, different neighborhoods may share similar social contexts, resulting in the confrontations of comparable governance issues or challenges.

5. Conclusion and limitations

In this paper, we have presented a novel clustering analytical framework for conducting typological studies on urban built forms. Existing clustering analyses in urban form studies usually rely on a single clustering algorithm or parameter setting, which may produce unstable or inconsistent clusters. Our framework aims to provide a stable solution and improve the quality of clusters by employing clustering ensembles. Clustering ensembles can integrate diverse clustering algorithms to capture different aspects of the underlying structure of the data. The use of clustering ensembles not only improves the synthesized results but also enhances their comprehensibility and generates new knowledge. Specifically, we utilized clustering ensembles along with five commonly used clustering algorithms in our research. By applying this framework to analyze the 3D building data of Guangzhou, we narrowed it down to one of the results and identified eight typologies of built forms at the scale of a 500 m grid. We also revealed a polycentric pattern among different results obtained from various algorithms. In particular, we observed that the primary urban area of Guangzhou demonstrates a core structure with three corridors, whereas the small urban areas exhibit a concentric circle pattern. This spatial structure remains consistent across various clustering algorithms, even when employing different parameter configurations and grid scales of 250 m, 500 m, and 750 m. These findings support the assertions made in official planning documents and corroborate previous studies that relied on alternative data sources. Our study holds significant implications for decision-making in large-scale urban development, urban governance, form-based coding, and urban design practices.
This study has certain limitations that need to be acknowledged and may be addressed in future studies. First, given the absence of definitive ground truth for built-form typology, evaluating the clustering ensembles’ results can be challenging using external measures. Although clustering ensembles offer diverse perspectives on the data structure, they do not guarantee superior classification results. Nevertheless, this approach mitigates the reliance on a single algorithm, thereby reducing the associated risks. Second, the selected built-form indicators significantly affect the clustering results. Considering the lack of a universally accepted criterion for collecting built-form features based on these indicators, their selection heavily relies on domain knowledge, local context, and research objectives. Moreover, if one places emphasis on a particular perspective, such as density, by selecting a large number of related indicators, the clustering algorithms might prioritize that perspective during the classification process. Future studies could explore alternative methods for objectively measuring these features using 3D building data. Additionally, the modifiable areal unit problem represents another limitation. In this study, we adopted grid sizes of 250 m, 500 m, and 750 m, aligning with common block sizes and previous studies conducted in similar cities. Our conclusion can only be drawn from these scales. Lastly, the k value of cluster ensembles is difficult to determine to present a concise and compressible result. In this study, we focused on the result with k=8. However, we still find highly similar typologies such as clusters 4 and 7, as well as clusters 6 and 11, in the identified typologies. From a data perspective, they are distinctive from specific indicators, but these distinctions are not so important based on the domain knowledge of built forms regarding their corresponding types. Future research can attempt to develop a semi-supervised approach to proofread the typologies.
